@NODE E.intro "Introduction"


@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}finds all duplicates in any collection of files.


It lists all files in one or two directories (or directory trees); compares
any pair of files having the same size; and finds all pairs whose files have
the same contents, even if they have distinct filenames.


You know the problem. You have huge collections of files (pictures, music
modules, audio samples, etc.) downloaded from different web sites or extracted
from distinct CD-ROMs. Often you have one or more duplicates of certain files,
because distinct sources used different filenames for the same file. You can
find duplicates manually, but actually this is convenient only in a small
collection. When your collection is formed by hundreds or thousands of files
the only reasonable way to find duplicates is a program that does the job for
you. As far as I know, all usual @{i}compare @{ui}programs make comparisons
between files having the same filename, and so they are generally useless in
the present case. Here is the point where @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}comes in
handy.


@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}is carefully optimized for maximum speed. Almost all the
processing time is used by external programs called by the routine. Actually
the present version of @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}(V2.3) is 10 to 300 times faster
than the first Aminet release (V1.8): it needs a few minutes to scan over 1
Gigabyte of files! Now @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}is so fast that it runs exactly
at the same speed of the ARexx-compiled version (not distributed). More
details are reported in the section @{"Speed" LINK E.speed}.


With @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}it is also possible to delete automatically all
duplicates found in a search. Even substitution of all duplicates with links
is possible.


@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}can be used from within Directory Opus.


@{FG SHINE}Operation details:@{FG TEXT} @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}scans the
directories involved calling the @{b}Dir @{ub}and @{b}List @{ub}commands, then
sorts the output with the @{b}Sort @{ub}command, and finally operates
internally to find all pairs of files with equal size. The files of each of
these pairs are compared by means of the @{b}cmp @{ub}command to ascertain if
they are actually equal. Finally the @{b}Sort @{ub}and @{b}Type @{ub}commands
are used to reorder and output the results, and the @{b}Delete @{ub}command is
used to eliminate all temporary files. When required, the @{b}Delete
@{ub}command is also used to remove all the duplicates, and the @{b}MakeLink
@{ub}command is used to replace all the duplicates with hardlinks.


@{FG SHINE}External requirements:@{FG TEXT} @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}makes use of
@{"cmp" LINK E.cmp} by @{"Alex Kazik" LINK E.thank}, that is in my opinion the
best @{i}compare @{ui}program ever written for the Amiga computer.


@{FG SHINE}System requirements:@{FG TEXT} AmigaOS 2.04 or better, RexxMast
running. @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}uses the C:List, C:Sort, C:Type, C:Delete, and
C:MakeLink commands. Be sure you have the original OS commands or absolutely
equivalent substitutes!


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.insta "Installation"


Copy @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} into your AREXX: directory and the documentation
wherever you want.


Download AmiNet:util/cli/ALeXcompare.lha and install @{b}cmp@{ub} following
its instructions.


@{FG SHINE}Note 1:@{FG TEXT} @{b}cmp@{ub} should be made resident, or must
be in C: or in your command path! Elsewhere the correct path should be
notified to @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}by inserting it at the beginning of the
code (instructions are given in the code).


@{FG SHINE}Note 2:@{FG TEXT} Be sure you download the most recent version
(V1.5 or later) of @{b}cmp@{ub} from Aminet! This version can be made
resident, thus giving a relevant speed gain when it is called repeatedly by
EqFiles.rexx.


@ENDNODE

