@NODE E.usage "Usage"


@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} @{i}can be run by typing the following command string
@{ui}


rx EqFiles.rexx <dir1> [<dir2>] [ALL] [DELETE] [LINK] [NODL] [NORES] [FILE[S]]
[SIZE>x] [INPAT=y] [EXPAT=z] [ICONS]


@{i}in a shell window (optional arguments are surrounded by square
brackets).@{ui}



@{FG SHINE}rx@{FG TEXT}

@{i}The starter program @{ui}@{b}rx@{ub} @{i}can be omitted if you activate
the script bit of @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} @{i}(to do this just type
@{ui}ProtectĀAREXX:EqFiles.rexxĀ+s @{i}in a shell window).@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}.rexx@{FG TEXT}

@{i}This extension is optional for @{ui}WShell @{i}users (like me). They can
omit both the starter program @{ui}@{b}rx@{ub} @{i}(don't worry about the
script bit!) and the @{ui}@{b}.rexx@{ub} @{i}extension.@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}<dir1> <dir2>@{FG TEXT}

@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}scans all files in directories @{ui}@{b}<dir1>
@{ub}@{i}and @{ui}@{b}<dir2>@{ub}, @{i}selects all pairs formed by a file
belonging to @{ui}@{b}<dir1> @{ub}@{i}and a file belonging to @{ui}@{b}<dir2>
@{ub}@{i}that have the same size, compares the first and second file of each
of these pairs, and detects and lists all pairs formed by equal files.
@{ui}@{b}<dir1> @{ub}@{i}and/or @{ui}@{b}<dir2> @{ub}@{i}can be specific
directories or generic sets of directories recovered by any legal AmigaDOS
directory pattern.@{ui}


@{i}When @{ui}@{b}<dir2> @{ub}@{i}is not specified, @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx
@{ub}@{i}assumes that @{ui}@{b}<dir1> @{ub}@{i}and @{ui}@{b}<dir2>
@{ub}@{i}are the same directory. Then it proceeds as above but carefully
avoids stupid or useless actions (like comparing a file with itself, or
comparing file B with file A after file A was already compared with file
B).@{ui}


@{i}@{u}You must specify at least one directory or directory pattern,
otherwise @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}will complain.@{uu} You can use two
adjacent quotes to specify the current directory, or a colon to specify the
current root.@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}ALL@{FG TEXT}

@{i}When the optional parameter @{ui}@{b}ALL @{ub}@{i}is specified, the search
for equal files is done recursively in all the subdirectories of
@{ui}@{b}<dir1> @{ub}@{i}(and of @{ui}@{b}<dir2> @{ub}@{i}if it was
specified).@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}DELETE@{FG TEXT}

@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}deletes all the duplicates found, if the optional
parameter @{ui}@{b}DELETE @{ub}@{i}is specified. When two distinct directories
are supplied, all and only the duplicates in @{ui}@{b}<dir2> @{ub}@{i}are
deleted. Be careful with this parameter: deletion will be always forced, even
if the files involved are protected against deletion!@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}LINK@{FG TEXT}

@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}replaces all the duplicates found with hardlinks,
if the optional parameter @{ui}@{b}LINK @{ub}@{i}is specified. When two
distinct directories are supplied, all and only the duplicates in
@{ui}@{b}<dir2> @{ub}@{i}are replaced by links. Be careful with this
parameter: it automatically activates also the @{ui}@{b}DELETE
@{ub}@{i}parameter! Deletion of duplicates is forced just before their
replacement with hardlinks, even if the files involved are protected against
deletion! Only hardlinks are supported: you cannot specify two directories
stored on distict disks/partitions together with the @{ui}@{b}LINK @{ub}@{i}
parameter.@{ui}


@{i}@{u}This option is particularly convenient when the directory/file
structure must be absolutely preserved as it is, and nevertheless a gain in
available disk space is still needed.@{uu}@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}NODL@{FG TEXT}

@{i}When you use directory pattern(s), @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}expands
them and automatically types in the shell window a list of all the directories
scanned. This can be very useful since you will see the directories actually
recovered by the pattern(s), and possibly can change the patterns if you get
undesired results. However the list of all the directories scanned can be very
long if you have large directory trees and/or use almost omni-comprehensive
directory patterns. In such a case you can specify the optional parameter
@{ui}@{b}NODL @{ub}@{i}to prevent the output of the directory list.@{ui}


@{i}(You can also preserve the lists of all the directories scanned in two
files: see the @{ui}@{b}FILES @{ub}@{i}optional parameter.)@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}NORES@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Usually @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}types in the shell window a list of
all the pairs of equal files detected in the directories supplied. The option
@{ui}@{b}NORES @{ub}@{i}can be used to specify to the program that no result
must be typed into the shell window, except confirmation texts and statistical
comments. You can use this optional parameter if you absolutely need brief
outputs and only statistical data are relevant for your purposes.@{ui}


@{i}@{u}This option is particularly convenient when it is activated together
with the @{ui}@{b}FILE @{ub}@{i}option (see below).@{uu}@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}FILE@{FG TEXT} or @{FG SHINE}FILES@{FG TEXT}

@{i}The list of all pairs of equal files typed by @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx
@{ub}@{i}in the current shell window can be very long in case of large
directories. If there are too many equal files, the text output can easily
overflow the shell history buffer (if you have one). Specifying the optional
parameter @{ui}@{b}FILE @{ub}@{i}you prevent the deletion of the temporary
file @{ui}T:EF_<id>_Result@{i}, where you can subsequently read a full copy of
the shell output.@{ui}


@{i}The hexadecimal number @{ui}<id> @{i}inserted in the previous filename
uniquely identifies each copy of @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}, and all the
relevant files, in case multiple copies have been run concurrently.@{ui}


@{i}@{u}Please note that the old form of this option is still accepted for
compatibility, but is useful mostly for debugging purposes.@{uu} In fact,
specifying this optional parameter in the alternative form @{ui}@{b}FILES
@{ub}@{i}, you prevent the deletion of all the temporary files created by
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}. Besides the above mentioned file
@{ui}T:EF_<id>_Result@{i}, the routine always creates the file
@{ui}T:EF_<id>_FList@{i}, that contains the list of all the files scanned by
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}(belonging to all the directories or directory
patterns possibly specified by the user). The files @{ui}T:EF_<id>_DList1
@{i}and/or @{ui}T:EF_<id>_DList2 @{i}are created only in case of directory
patterns: here you will find the lists of all the directories scanned by
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}during its operation.@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}SIZE>x@{FG TEXT}

@{i}The presence of many small files in the directories to be scanned will
increase the processing time, even if you don't care of those files. This
option, where @{ui}@{b}x @{ub}@{i}is a positive or null integer, will force
the program to reject all files whose size is smaller than, or equal to,
@{ui}@{b}x@{ub}.@{i} A careful choice of the value of @{ui}@{b}x @{ub}@{i}can
dramatically increase the performing speed of @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx
@{ub}@{i}without affecting the comparisons you really need.@{ui}


@{i}The option @{ui}@{b}SIZE>0 @{ub}@{i}is meaningful but almost useless: it
excludes only empty files from comparisons.@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}INPAT=y@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Here @{ui}@{b}y @{ub}@{i}can be any AmigaDOS filename pattern. Only files
whose filenames match this pattern will be accepted for comparisons. The
default pattern is @{ui}(#?)@{i}, which means that all files will be accepted
(except those possibly excluded by means of the @{ui}@{b}EXPAT
@{ub}@{i}parameter, see below).


@{i}@{u}Please note that only the simple filename is affected by this pattern.
You must never specify the path here! Paths are controlled exclusively by
directory patterns (see above).@{uu}@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}EXPAT=z@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Here @{ui}@{b}z @{ub}@{i}can be any AmigaDOS filename pattern. All files
whose filenames match this pattern will be rejected. The default pattern is
@{ui}(#?.INFO)@{i}, which means that icon files will never be compared. If you
explicitly specify a pattern, it will be automatically @{ui}AND@{i}'ed with
@{ui}(#?.INFO) @{i}in order to exclude always icons files.


You can change this behaviour by specifying the @{ui}@{b}ICONS
@{ub}@{i}parameter (see below). In such a case the default value for the
@{ui}@{b}z @{ub}@{i}pattern will be @{ui}~(#?)@{i}, which means that no file
will be rejected.


@{i}@{u}Please note that only the simple filename is affected by this pattern.
You must never specify the path here! Paths are controlled exclusively by
directory patterns (see above).@{uu}@{ui}


@{FG SHINE}ICONS@{FG TEXT}

@{i}Generally you should not take care of icon comparisons: icons will be
automatically rejected by default (see above). Nevertheless, if you want to
admit icons in comparisons, you can specify this optional parameter.@{i}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}During its operation @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}will type brief
messages that describe the currently executed operation. They are:@{ui}


Parsing input string...

Expanding patterns...

Acquiring data...

Preprocessing data...

Processing file M of N in <dir1>


@{i}For directories containing a small number of files, these messages will appear
and disappear so fast that possibly you will not be able to read them. Their
purpose, in fact, is mainly for large directories and long processing times.
In such a case you will always know what operation is being executed.


The last message is a progress indicator. The fixed number @{ui}N @{i}is the
total number of files in @{ui}<dir1> @{i}, while the variable number @{ui}M
@{i}represents the file in @{ui}<dir1> @{i}currently processed.



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}In case of errors, @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}will type
self-explanatory messages. Wrong command syntax and erroneous operation will
be clearly notified, so you will be always able to correct your command line.


Here is a list of the error messages typed by @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}@{i},
with the relevant exit codes set by the routine when it stops:@{ui}


 5   @{b}User break!@{ub}

 5   @{b}Illegal number of @{ub} " @{b} delimiters!@{ub}

 5   @{b}Illegal use of @{ub} " @{b} delimiters!@{ub}

 5   @{b}You must specify at least one directory!@{ub}

 5   @{b}Option @{ub} ... @{b} not allowed!@{ub}

 5   @{b}Wrong @{ub}SIZE@{b} specification!@{ub}

10   @{b}No (allowed) files in directory @{ub} ...

20   @{b}<dir1> @{ub} ... @{b} not found: erroneous directory name/pattern!@{ub}

20   @{b}<dir2> @{ub} ... @{b} not found: erroneous directory name/pattern!@{ub}

20   @{b}Hardlinks cannot be set among distinct disks/partitions!@{ub}


@{i}You can always stop @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}by pressing
@{ui}CTRL-C. @{i}This causes a @{ui}BREAK @{i}instantly, unless at that time
an AmigaDOS command has been run by the ARexx routine. In such a case you have
to wait that the AmigaDOS command quits and returns control to
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Due to the use of directory patterns, the output of
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}is changed a little with respect to the first
Aminet release. In all later versions any pair of equal files is always
signalled by prepending their whole path to the filename. For deep directory
trees this means larger and somewhat less readable outputs, but there is an
advantage in terms of clearer file identification and higher processing
speed.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}As in all previous versions, @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} @{i}makes
use of ANSI codes in order to obtain a more readable coloured output. If the
colours chosen by me for my workbench palette are not good with your own
palette, you may change them. Search the code for expressions of the type
@{ui}<ESC>[3?m @{i}where the wildcard @{ui}? @{i}represents one of the figures
@{ui}1, 2, ..., 7. @{i}Then try to replace the figure @{ui}? @{i}with another
one. These figures represent workbench colours (respectively colour @{ui}2, 3,
..., 8 @{i}of the workbench palette).@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Please note the programming attempt to make fool-proof the parsing
routine that interprets the arguments you type. A number of explanatory
comments are printed in case of errors. Please let me know if you are so fool
(eh eh...) to obtain an improper operation.@{ui}



@ENDNODE

@NODE E.examp "Examples"


@{i}To obtain the template and a brief help text you can type @{ui}
rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀ? @{i}in a shell window: @{ui}


1.RD0:> rx EqFiles.rexx ?


@{BG SHINE}EqFiles V2.3 by Fulvio Peruggi - January 1, 2000@{BG BACKGROUND}


@{FG SHINE}Usage: [rx] EqFiles[.rexx] <dir1> [<dir2>] [ALL] [DELETE] [LINK] [NODL]

                 [NORES] [FILE[S]] [SIZE>x] [INPAT=y] [EXPAT=z] [ICONS]@{FG TEXT}

@{b}EqFiles@{ub} scans all files in directories @{b}<dir1>@{ub} and @{b}<dir2>@{ub}, compares each file

  in @{b}<dir1>@{ub} with every file in @{b}<dir2>@{ub} having the same size, and lists all

  pairs of equal files detected.

@{b}<dir1>@{ub} and/or @{b}<dir2>@{ub} can be explicit directory names or legal AmigaDOS

  patterns. If @{b}<dir2>@{ub} is not specified, @{b}<dir2>@{ub}=@{b}<dir1>@{ub} by default.

Command operations act on the files in all subdirectories of the given

  directories if the optional parameter @{b}ALL@{ub} is specified.

Equal files found in @{b}<dir2>@{ub} are deleted and notified if the optional parameter

  @{b}DELETE@{ub} is specified.

Equal files found in @{b}<dir2>@{ub} are substituted by hardlinks and notified if the

  optional parameter @{b}LINK@{ub} is specified.

The program always types a list of all directories recovered by the patterns,

  unless the optional parameter @{b}NODL@{ub} is specified.

The program always types a list of all pairs of equal files detected, unless

  the optional parameter @{b}NORES@{ub} is specified.

The optional parameter @{b}FILE@{ub} (or @{b}FILES@{ub}) prevents the deletion of the

  @{b}T:EF_<id>_Result@{ub} file (respctively all the files) created in @{b}T:@{ub} by @{b}EqFiles@{ub}.

The optional parameter @{b}SIZE>x@{ub}, where @{b}x@{ub} is a non-negative integer, prevents

  comparisons between files with size lower than, or equal to, @{b}x@{ub}.

The optional parameters @{b}INPAT=y@{ub} and/or @{b}EXPAT=z@{ub}, where @{b}y@{ub} and @{b}z@{ub} must be legal

  AmigaDOS patterns, can be used to select and/or reject all files whose

  filenames match the patterns.                                         

By default, icons are never compared unless the optional parameter @{b}ICONS@{ub}

  is specified.



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}The following command will search the whole Workbench for equal
files (icons excluded):@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀHD0: all

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}When @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}expands the paths supplied, it
substitutes device physical names (such as @{ui}HD0:@{i}) with their logical
names (that is @{ui}Workbench:@{i}, in this case). This is an effect of the
internal routines.


The @{ui}PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))" @{i}typed by @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx
@{ub}@{i}is the complex file pattern that it creates and supplies to the
@{ui}List @{i}command. AmigaDOS patterns lacks for the @{ui}AND @{i}Boolean
operator, so it is reconstructed by means of @{ui}OR @{i}operators, negation
operators, and DeĀMorgan rules. In this case @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx
@{ub}@{i}has used the default file patterns already mentioned in the
@{ui}@{"Usage" LINK E.usage} @{i}section.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}The following command will search all (and only) the first level
subdirectories of the Workbench for equal files (icons included):@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀWorkbench:#? icons

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ICONS PAT="~(~(#?)|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

  <dir1> Workbench:C/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Classes/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Devs/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Expansion/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Fonts/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:L/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Libs/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Locale/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:OTHER/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Prefs/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Rexxc/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:S/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Storage/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:System/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:T/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Tools/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:Utilities/  ...scanned

  <dir1> Workbench:WBStartup/  ...scanned

Workbench:Fonts/CGTimes.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/CGTriumvirate.font

Workbench:Fonts/CGTimes.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/LetterGothic.font

Workbench:Fonts/CGTriumvirate.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/LetterGothic.font

@{FG FILL}249 files found in <dir1>. @{FG  FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08B566B8

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}3 pairs of equal files detected.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}


@{i}Note that the explicit pattern supplied here by us is a directory pattern!
So the @{ui}Workbench:#?/ @{i}symbol does not represent files in the Workbench
root. It represents only directories in the Workbench root.


Also note that @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}always emphasizes the
distinction between directories and files by displaying explicitly a slash
after the last directory name/pattern in a path.


The @{ui}<id> @{i}specification is used to identify the files generated by
each @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}process. In this example we have
@{ui}<id>=08B566B8 @{i}: every other @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}process
that will be run concurrently will get a distinct @{ui}<id>@{i}. However, note
that two @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}processes can get the same @{ui}<id>
@{i}if one is run @{u}after@{uu} the other ends. In this case the last process
will delete or overwrite all the files with the common @{ui}<id> @{i}that were
created by the previous process.



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This command is the same as above, but the option @{ui}NODL
@{i}now prevents the output of the directory list:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀWorkbench:#?/ nodl icons

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: NODL ICONS PAT="~(~(#?)|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

Workbench:Fonts/CGTimes.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/CGTriumvirate.font

Workbench:Fonts/CGTimes.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/LetterGothic.font

Workbench:Fonts/CGTriumvirate.font @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Fonts/LetterGothic.font

@{FG FILL}249 files found in <dir1>. @{FG  FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08B56AB8

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}3 pairs of equal files detected.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This command will search all second level subdirectories of the
Workbench for equal files (icons excluded):@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀWorkbench:#?/#?

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:#?/#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This command will search all second level and deeper level
subdirectories of the Workbench for equal files (icons included):@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀWorkbench:#?/#? all icons

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:#?/#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL ICONS PAT="~(~(#?)|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This command will search @{ui}Workbench:Devs/Monitors @{i}and all
subdirectories of @{ui}Workbench:Devs @{i}for equal files (icons
excluded):@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀWorkbench:Devs/Monitors Workbench:Devs/#? all

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/Monitors/"@{ub}

     and <dir2>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/clipboards/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/DOSDrivers/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Keymaps/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/DataTypes/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Monitors/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Printers/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Kickstarts/  ...scanned

@{FG FILL}3 files found in <dir1>; 34 files found in <dir2>. @{FG  FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08A78588

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}No equal files detected.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}


@{i}No equal files were detected even if all files in
@{ui}Workbench:Devs/Monitors @{i}are contained in Workbench:Devs/#? and are
obviously equal to themselves. @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}automatically
excludes these trivial comparisons. However, note that two equal files both
contained into @{ui}Workbench:Devs/Monitors@{i} will be signalled.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This is the same command given above, but now we have inserted a
copy of @{ui}Multiscan @{i}in @{ui}Workbench:Devs/Monitors @{i}using the name
@{ui}TestFile@{i}:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀHD0:Devs/Monitors HD0:Devs/#? all

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/Monitors/"@{ub}

     and <dir2>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/clipboards/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/DOSDrivers/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Keymaps/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/DataTypes/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Monitors/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Printers/  ...scanned

  <dir2> Workbench:Devs/Kickstarts/  ...scanned

Workbench:Devs/Monitors/Multiscan @{FG SHINE}==@{FG TEXT} Workbench:Devs/Monitors/TestFile

@{FG FILL}4 files found in <dir1>; 35 files found in <dir2>. @{FG  FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08A78598

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}1 pair of equal files detected.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}


@{i}The copy has been detected and signalled.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This is the same command given above, but now we have prevented
directory listing and forced deletion of the copy:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀHD0:Devs/Monitors HD0:Devs/#? all nodl delete

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/Monitors/"@{ub}

     and <dir2>: @{b}"Workbench:Devs/#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

Workbench:Devs/Monitors/Multiscan @{FG SHINE}==@{FG  HIGHLIGHT} Workbench:Devs/Monitors/TestFile

@{FG FILL}4 files found in <dir1>; 35 files found in <dir2>. @{FG  FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08A7A420

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}1 pair of equal files detected. Highlighted file has been deleted.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}


@{i}The copy has been detected and deleted.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}This command is a more complex example. It will compare files
belonging to any second level subdirectory of @{ui}HD0: @{i}(and all their
subdirectories) with files belonging to any subdirectory of @{ui}HD1:
@{i}whose name starts with @{ui}"dtp" @{i}or @{ui}"c<anycharacter>m"@{i} (and
all their subdirectories). Icons will be excluded from comparisons.@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexxĀHD0:#?/#? HD1:(dtp|c?m)#? all

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Workbench:#?/#?/"@{ub}

     and <dir2>: @{b}"Work:(dtp|c?m)#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}My @{ui}HD1: @{i}partition is just the @{ui}Work: @{i}volume, and contains
two directories named @{ui}DTP-WP @{i}and @{ui}Communications@{i}, so this is
meaningful for me (for your information, in directories so much different for
their contents there were four pairs of equal files: all of them were empty
preference files).@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Please note that the directory pattern expansion routine is smart
enough to recognize and resolve also equivocal expressions. For example,
assume that @{ui}RD0: @{i}contains only four subdirectories named @{ui}1 @{i},
@{ui}2 @{i}, @{ui}3 @{i}, @{ui}4 @{i}. Then the command:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexx RD0:#? RD0:(1|2|3|4)

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

  <dir1> RD0:1/  ...scanned

  <dir1> RD0:2/  ...scanned

  <dir1> RD0:3/  ...scanned

  <dir1> RD0:4/  ...scanned

...


@{i}produces the previous comment since @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} @{i}knows
that the two directory patterns supplied as input are actually only one
pattern expressed in two equivalent ways.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Directory patterns can be freely mixed with filename
patterns:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexx HD2:Pic#? inpat=#?.jpg

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"Data:Pic#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?.jpg))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}This command examines only the @{ui}.jpg @{i}pictures present in the
directories of @{ui}HD2: @{i}(logical name @{ui}Data:@{i}) whose name starts
with the letters @{ui}Pic @{i}(icons are excluded).



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Here is an example concerning the exclusion filename pattern:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexx "" expat=#?.gif icons

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:"@{ub}

   Options used: ICONS PAT="~(~(~(#?.gif))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}This command rejects all @{ui}.gif @{i}pictures present in the current
directory, and examines all the other files (icons included).@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Another example concerning the exclusion filename pattern:@{ui}


1.RD0:> rxĀEqFiles.rexx :#? expat=#?.gif

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:#?/"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~((#?.INFO)|(#?.gif)))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}This command rejects all @{ui}.gif @{i}pictures, and examines all the
other files present in the first level subdirectories of the current root: the
filename pattern is automatically modified to exclude icons, too.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}Both filename patterns can be used at the same time. Example:@{ui}


1.RD0:Texts> rx EqFiles.rexx /Pics&Movies inpat=r#? expat=#?.(mpg|mpeg)

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:Pics&Movies/"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~((#?.INFO)|(#?.(mpg|mpeg))))|~(r#?))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}Note that the current directory now is @{ui}RD0:Texts@{i}. The command
asks @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}to go into the upper directory @{ui}RD0:
@{i}and then into the subdirectory @{ui}Pics&Movies@{i}. There it should
accept only files whose name starts with letter @{ui}r @{i}, and should reject
all @{ui}.mpg @{i}and @{ui}.mpeg @{i}movies, as well as icons, possibly
present among these files.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}To allow spaces in a filename, dirname, or pattern, simply
surround the specific argument involved with quotes. Example:@{ui}


1.RD0:>rx EqFiles.rexx : "inpat=#? #?.jpg"

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:"@{ub}

   Options used: PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#? #?.jpg))"@{FG TEXT}

...


@{i}This command examines all @{ui}.jpg @{i}pictures, present in the current
root, that have a space in their filename.



@ENDNODE

@NODE E.hints "Hints"


@{i}If you don't use a hard disk cache program, please make @{ui}@{b}cmp
@{ub}@{i}resident for faster performance.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}@{u}You must be aware of the fact that the computer could get
confused by filenames and dirnames containing special characters used by
AmigaDOS for pattern matching.@{uu}


For example a directory whose name starts with the @{ui}@{b}~
@{ub}@{i}character locks the @{ui}List @{i}command into an infinite loop,
causing @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}to hang up without notice. Another
example is a directory whose name contains the @{ui}@{b}% @{ub}@{i}character:
it forces the @{ui}List @{i}command to abort abruptly emitting an error code
@{ui}20 @{i}: so, in this case, @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}does not hang
up, but it will not detect and check all the files (all those belonging to
directories that follows the one with the illegal name in the scan order used
by the @{ui}List @{i}command will be skipped!). A final example that can be
mentioned is a problem that occurs when there are dirnames or filenames
containing the @{ui}@{b}( @{ub}@{i}and @{ui}@{b}) @{ub}@{i}characters. The
AmigaDOS @{ui}List @{i}command does not detect any file contained in
directories with such dirnames, and thus @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}will
never make comparisons between files contained therein. Furthermore, when
files with such filenames exist, the @{ui}DELETE @{i}option of
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}will fail because the AmigaDOS @{ui}Delete
@{i}command will not be able to find (!) those files. Thus
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}will report that certain files have been
deleted, but those with parentheses in the filename will still be there...


@{u}These are not my faults! Please be certain that all your files and
directories have legal AmigaDOS names.@{uu}@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}If you have unexpected results when using quotes, please remember
that any single argument of @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}can be surrounded
by quotes. Don't surround many arguments at the same time with two quotes
since they will be erroneously seen as a single argument and most probably a
syntax error condition will occur! An input string such as@{ui}


1.RD0:>rx EqFiles.rexx RD0: "nodl size>6000 inpat=#? #?.jpg icons"


@{i}will be rejected. Use instead the following one:@{ui}


1.RD0:>rx EqFiles.rexx RD0: "nodl" "size>6000" "inpat=#? #?.jpg" "icons"


@{i}Quotes are actually needed only for file/directory names/patterns when
they contain one or more blanks. So in this case the simplest input line will
be:@{ui}


1.RD0:>rx EqFiles.rexx RD0: nodl size>6000 "inpat=#? #?.jpg" icons



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}If @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}types a message of the type


@{ui}@{b}No (allowed) files in directory @{ub}"RD0:"@{b} !@{ub}


@{i}and the mentioned directory is not empty, maybe the problem is caused by
the inclusion and/or exclusion filename patterns you have specified. It is
very easy to select clashing patterns that actually exclude any filename from
being considered. Of course, this is your fault! And don't forget that icon
files are excluded by default unless otherwise stated with the @{ui}ICONS
@{i}option.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}The @{ui}LINK @{i}option greatly improves the usefulness of
@{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}for collections of files where there are many
duplicates that cannot be simply deleted, since some programs should access
them sometimes. In this case the best solution is to replace all these files
except one with links to the surviving file. So the collection of files is
reduced in size, while its compatibility with any external program that access
the files is preserved by the links. Typical examples of this case are many
collections of instruments or sound samples.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}If you use many times the @{ui}FILE @{i}(or @{ui}FILES@{i}) option
on big directories, please remember that the undeleted files in the @{ui}T:
@{i}directory will make it grow, so you will lose plenty of RAM. You may need
to manually delete the files that are no more useful.@{ui}



@{JCENTER}@{FG SHINE}----------------@{FG TEXT}



@{JLEFT}@{i}If you have a "strange" directory whose name is equal to some
option of @{ui}@{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}@{i}, the routine will not be able to
recognize that directory unless you input it with its full path. For
example, assume you want to scan a directory named @{ui}Size> @{i}in
@{ui}RD0:@{i}. This command will fail:@{ui}


RD0:> rx EqFiles.rexx "Size>" all


@{b}You must specify at least one directory!@{ub}


@{i}This command will work:@{ui}


RD0:> rx EqFiles.rexx "RD0:Size>" all

@{FG FILLTEXT}Scanning <dir1>: @{b}"RD0:Size>/"@{ub}

   Options used: ALL PAT="~(~(~(#?.INFO))|~(#?))"@{FG TEXT}

@{FG FILL}1 file found in <dir1>. @{FG FILLTEXT}Process <id>: 08A777C8

@{FG SHINE}@{BG TEXT}No equal files detected.@{FG TEXT}@{BG BACK}


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.speed "Speed"


A program like @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}can be really useful only if it is fast.
So in this section there are detailed reports about speed changes that occur
upgrading from one Aminet release to the following.


@{FG SHINE}Second Aminet release (V2.2) --> Third Aminet release (V2.3)
@{FG TEXT}


The elimination of two bugs in the main routine forced me to add a number of
additional checks in it. This caused an overall slow down, so I revised
completely the main routine hoping to regain the speed loss. A careful
reduction/optimization of the code produced a 10% speed up of the program.
Moreover, following a suggestion by @{"Christopher Eburn" LINK E.thank} I
removed all the @{b}left() @{ub}and @{b}substr() @{ub}functions used in the
main routine and substituted them with invocations of the @{b}parse
@{ub}instruction. The execution of this instruction is slightly faster than
the execution of the former functions (and its use also made it possible to
improve the readability of the EF_<id>_FList file). This trick made it
possible to obtain another 1%-3% gain in the processing speed.


Therefore, in conclusion, the main routine is now bug free and even shorter
than before. @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}is 5% faster than the previous version when
two distinct non-nested directories are compared, and is about 3% faster when
applied to a single directory or two nested directories.


@{FG SHINE}First Aminet release (V1.8) --> Second Aminet release (V2.2)
@{FG TEXT}


Very relevant speed gains were obtained in this case. Let us consider the
typical processing times of these versions of @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}, assuming
that they are used to scan a single directory (tree) containing a total number
N of files.


Both the routines use approximately the same time to list all the files
involved and sort their filenames. Both the routines make the same number of
actual comparisons by calling @{b}cmp@{ub} for all pairs of files having equal
sizes.


In the worst case, that is when all the files to check have the same size, the
two routines take approximately the same time to do their job. Indeed the time
spent is almost completely used by @{b}cmp@{ub} for its comparisons.


However in real cases, the number of pairs of files having equal size is only
a small fraction of the total number of pairs of files. Although @{b}cmp
@{ub}still uses the same time for its comparisons, both in V1.8 and V2.2, now
there is a large amount of internal ARexx processing. The code used in V1.8
executes a total number of steps roughly proportional to NūN, while the code
in V2.2 is much more optimized and executes a total number of steps roughly
proportional to N. Thus for a high number of files the performance differences
between V1.8 and V2.2 usually become huge.


For example, running @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}on a partition of an IDE hard disk
containing 10866 files in 550 directories for a total of 521744332 bytes
(505.8 Megabytes), both versions of the program found 281 pairs of equal
files, but V1.8 spent about 15 hours while V2.2 finished its job after 3
minutes and 43 seconds! The machine used was an Amiga 4000 equipped with a
CyberStormPPC (68060-50MHz/PPC-233MHz), the hard disk was accessed at 2.5
Megabytes/second, no cache programs such as
@{"Future Drive Accelerator" LINK "E.FDA"} or DynamiCache were used, and
@{b}cmp@{ub} was made resident.


In the previous case the speed gain was approximately equal to 250. During
normal use you should expect that V2.2 runs from 10 to 300 times faster than
V1.8, depending on the total number of pairs of files and the actual number of
pairs having equal size. Please note that this generally is true when a large
number of files is scanned. For a small number of files there can be no speed
gain at all.


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.multi "Multitasking"


All the previous versions of @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} cannot be run concurrently.
They used fixed filenames, so the attempt to launch a copy of
@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} while another one was already running caused the lock of
both routines when they attempted to delete/create/access the same files at
the same time.


I gave rise to such a problem some time ago. I run @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}to
scan a whole partition, where it took a few minutes to finish. In the
meanwhile I needed to apply the routine on other directories, and
inadvertently I didn't expect the end of the first process to start the second
one, causing the lock of both processes... Therefore I decided to finally
implement a very elegant and simple trick suggested to me by
@{"Alex Kazik" LINK E.thank} one year ago.


When a copy of @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} is run, it allocates one byte of RAM,
stores its address into the variable @{b}<id>@{ub}, and subsequently uses this
hexadecimal value like an identification mark, inserting it into the names of
all the files created and used by the routine. Since multiple copies of
@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} that run concurrently will be forced by the operating
system to allocate distinct bytes with different addresses, they will use
distinct @{b}<id>@{ub} marks in their filenames, without interfering each
other.


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.progs "Similar programs"


@{"Martin Tauchmann" LINK E.thank} made me aware of the existence of the
following programs, that operate on duplicate files in a way similar (in full
or only in part) to @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}:


Ę @{b}SeekSame @{ub}V1.3   by Stephan Fuhrmann (Stephan.Fuhrmann@stud.uni-karlsruhe.de)

Ę @{b}DupFinder @{ub}V1.0  by Kjell Irgens (kjelli@stud.cs.uit.no)

Ę @{b}Watch @{ub}V1.2      by Andreas L÷fgren (al@swipnet.se)


@{b}SeekSame @{ub}is unavailable both on Aminet and on Fish disks. Many
options of this program are similar to those provided by
@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}. This is an example of parallel evolution, because all
the options provided by previous versions of @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}were
developed by me independently. However, @{b}EqFiles.rexx @{ub}offers much more
options to the user, while @{b}SeekSame @{ub}unfortunately is also buggy! As
soon as I received the @{b}SeekSame @{ub}archive by Martin, I applied this
utility to my usual test directories, and it typed some results in the shell
window and then locked up! Since the MAKELINK option of @{b}SeekSame @{ub}is
almost unusable because of these bugs, Martin suggested that I should provide
its full functionality to the users by inserting a similar option into
@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}. So the LINK option is born. Many thanks are due to
Stephan Fuhrmann for the original idea.


@{b}DupFinder @{ub}is available on Aminet (disk/misc/DupFinder10.lha). This
program is fast, but it only detects duplicates, and does not allow the user
to operate on them in a suitable way, like @{b}SeekSame @{ub}and
@{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}.


@{b}Watch @{ub}is available on Aminet (util/misc/Watch.lha). Actually this
program has been written to execute other functions: it is aware of duplicate
files almost incidentally.


All these programs were written in C and of course are compiled. Unfortunately
it seems that they are no more updated since a few years.


Although @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub} is an interpreted ARexx management program that
relies on some external utilities for its functionality, it provides more
options, and in most cases is faster than all the above-mentioned programs!


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.histo "History"


@{u}Version 0.1-0.9@{uu} (01.04.98-30.04.98)

Ę Actually... prehistory. The prototype of all further versions was a program
named SearchEqFiles.rexx. It was subsequently replaced by two distinct
programs (FindEqFiles.rexx and DeleteEqFiles.rexx), that at last were
integrated again into a single program.


@{u}Version 1.0@{uu} (02.05.98)

Ę First fully working and integrated program.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.1@{uu} (09.05.98)

Ę Improved parsing routine.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.2@{uu} (16.05.98)

Ę Optimized comparisons.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.3@{uu} (30.05.98)

Ę Parsing routine rewritten from scratch.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.4@{uu} (31.05.98)

Ę Reworked comparison code to minimize hard disk accesses.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.5@{uu} (29.07.98)

Ę Modified file calling (filenames with spaces caused errors).

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.6@{uu} (03.09.98)

Ę Modified deletion routine: in some (rare) cases, files with equal length and
distinct contents were deleted.

Ę Internal release.


@{u}Version 1.7@{uu} (10.09.98)

Ę Improved parsing routine: now really fool-proof?

Ę Improved comparison code: speed gain.

Ę Created document file in AmigaGuide format.

Ę Beta-tester release.


@{u}Version 1.8@{uu} (11.10.98)

Ę Removed residual erroneous handling of filenames with spaces in case of
deletion.

Ę Major changes and additions in the document file.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Ę First Aminet release.@{FG TEXT}


@{u}Version 1.9@{uu} (05.11.98)

Ę @{"Andreas Meyer" LINK E.thank} kindly sent me this modified version of the
code that allows very fast comparisons. The new algorithm for the detection of
pairs of files having equal size was much faster than before, on the average,
but some minor bugs were introduced in the code.

Ę Unofficial hack (but very appreciated).


@{u}Version 2.0@{uu} (18.11.98)

Ę Further optimization of the main comparison routine.

Ę Added progress indicator.

Ę All known bugs removed.

Ę Beta-tester release.


@{u}Version 2.1@{uu} (11.01.99)

Ę Most code reorganized and/or rewritten from scratch.

Ę Added directory pattern matching.

Ę Added filename pattern matching with independent inclusion and exclusion
patterns.

Ę Added automatic exclusion of icon files (can be disabled).

Ę Added selectable exclusion of files smaller than a given size.

Ę Added selectable storing of the results into a file.

Ę Added CTRL-C trapping to avoid undesired shell cursor disabling when exiting
after a BREAK.

Ę Beta-tester release.


@{u}Version 2.2@{uu} (30.05.99)

Ę Modified the exit code to stop the routine without executing useless checks.

Ę Removed some bugs related to directory patterns (a few checks were missed
and a few checks were repeated).

Ę Added option NODL to prevent output of too long directory lists in case of
patterns.

Ę Improved parsing routine.

Ę Now every legal AmigaDOS pattern is accepted by the input check routine.

Ę Major changes and additions in the document file.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Ę Second Aminet release.@{FG TEXT}


@{u}Version 2.3@{uu} (01.01.00)

Ę Multiple copies of this utility can be run concurrently.

Ę Improved parsing routine: now the actual number of arguments is detected
dynamically.

Ę The input check routine accepts no more quoted options with trailing blanks.

Ę The input confirmation text typed by the program now is formatted.

Ę Removed a bug in the main routine: empty files were not discarded when the
SIZE>x option was specified.

Ę Removed another (long standing but rarely occurring) bug in the main
routine: sometimes some pairs of equal files were not detected when nested
directories were compared.

Ę Further optimization and speed up of the main routine.

Ę Suitable exit codes are set when program ends.

Ę Added LINK option for replacement of duplicates with hardlinks.

Ę Added NORES option to prevent any output except confirmation text and
statistical comments.

Ę Major changes and additions in the document file.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Ę Third Aminet release.@{FG TEXT}


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.bugs "Known bugs"


Ę It seems that a rare bug of the fast file system can give rise sometimes to
lock-up problems when the LINK option is used intensively on already existing
hardlinks. In any case this is a bug of the FFS and the Delete and/or MakeLink
command; definitively it is not a bug of @{b}EqFiles.rexx@{ub}, that actively
interacts with the environment only through AmigaDOS commands. Alternative
file systems, like PFS2 and PFS3, seem to be not affected.


@ENDNODE

@NODE E.todo "To do"


Ę Insert the capability to recognize and signal pairs of files where a file is
a truncated copy of the other.


Ę Insert a workaround to avoid the problem occurring sometimes with the LINK
option and FFS partitions (see @{"Known bugs" LINK "E.bugs"}).


Ę Remove residual bugs, hopefully none. (Please let me know if you find one.)


